 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uhaemish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Haemish</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoG Founder</span><br>  Posts: 568<br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/26/01 3:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.godwin.com/sd/haemish.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Guess on Dragon Raids</span><hr size=1> I have actually tried to encourage CoG guilds that are NOT currently in a rotation to do so, for many reasons. 1) To alleviate the guests problem that gets people so pissed off sometimes about loot they can't see straight, 2) To ease the burden on certain raid leaders in the CoG from feeling like they HAVE to run planes and dragons raids for smaller guilds who might otherwise not be able to go, and 3) To move the CoG's focus away from high level raids that seem to ultimately come down to who's getting what loot. <br>
<br>
The KGC, for better or worse is there for 1 thing: Peace. Everyone wants some of the loot off of the targets the KGC does rotations on. Better to agree beforehand on who gets what when and avoid the bickering that can cause such server wide animosity. On many other servers, the largest or most uber guilds can and will control whatever targets they want until they are tired of them. Imagine wanting to get a piece of planes armour, and not being able to get into the planes because every mob there has already been killed every night this week by one guild. For the last 6 months. Expand that to the Kunark dragons or Venril Sathir. Imagine every time one of those mobs popped, your guild having to race to get 30 people together and get the mob killed before someone else did. Imagine KSing arguments over VOX. Picture the problems we sometimes have in the Oasis over KSing and magnify that 100 times because the mob being argued over drops godlike loot. It's that kind of counterproductive bickering that burns people out on EQ at the high levels fast. <br>
<br>
The KGC is a give and take situation. Larger guilds who could own the planes every day of the week give up a little time there in the sake of peace. Smaller guilds save themselves the stress and bickering and also get a shot at some targets they might never be able to get if other guilds didn't agree to not attack a target. Is it the best system in the world? No. It is a system of as Lagdalen said, &quot;mutual self-interest&quot; though not necessarily enlightened self-interest. It makes mistakes, and it gets people pissed off sometimes, but I think it works. And I think for smaller guilds of less than say 30 planes capable people, alliances in the KGC work best. I wish I could get every small guild that has been to a CoG dragon or plane raid that DOESN'T have an alliance into one, and that the CoG could move away from dealing with the KGC as an entity. Because I think it distracts people from the real goal of the CoG, events that aren't tied into lewtz, experience or items. Just plain fun. <br>
<br>
I've rambled a bit, but that's that. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Haemish <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bcouncilofguilds.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=kellory>Kellory</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Unguilded Sexless Drood</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/26/01 5:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Guess on Dragon Raids</span><hr size=1> Heh, actually I think I was the one that made the mutual self-interest jibe there. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Unless Lag said it first somewhere else.  In which case I take full responsibility for plagarism and ask for my spanking now please. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Only from Lag tho...<br>
<br>
On a more serious note I would add that I'm not a fan of how KGC is run.  Mutual self interest is fine so long as you can agree on what best defines a compromise.  On the other hand it is a far sight better than the total FFA anarchy that happens on most other servers.  You really need to have played on one of those servers to understand the level of animosity that Haemish was talking about.  The thought of an how long a guild like Valoran (Sorry Lag just needed an example) could monopolize Hate or Fear is mind boggling.  So there is much to be said for KGC.  Still their insistance on frowning upon double dipping can really keep smaller guilds and alliances from ever getting to the Planes.  And I've said thats just the begining of your post 51 raid experience.<br>
<br>
For all of the guilds listed in alliances I can name dozens that are not planes capable and probably never will be.  This is in part because they are unable to field enough people.  As they gain planes capable players they lose them just as quickly to other guilds.  So can CoG actually field enough people just from their non planar/dragon capable guilds to run these raids on their own?  I would have to say probably not.  At least from the numbers and guilds that I've seen show up.  It seems that as soon as we get some good people something happens to put us back to square one.  Which pretty much sums it up for many other guilds out there as well.  <br>
<br>
Solution?  You've got me.  Run more raids perhaps.  Encourage people not to leave their guilds.  Take a firmer stance on guests maybe.  The last is hard since that would pretty much exclude everyone on my friends list (short tho it may be these days) and its not much fun raiding without friends.  And I'm sure it'd be the same for many others out there.<br>
<br>
One thing tho.  Expect things like this to come up a lot.  Like it or not many of our best and most experienced players are part of planes capable alliances or guilds and double dipping will happen, if for no other reason than when you need someone to cover your back you'll call for a friend.<br>
<br>
What was the point of all this?  Now that I re-read it I'm not entirely sure, but I'm too tired to redo it.  So take it as it is.  Sort of a rant sort of my own personal philosophy on this.  Perhaps if we too meditate on these facts we can learn some Tai Kwan Leap.<br>
<br>
